    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white text-center">The Gallery Structure That Actually Gets Indexed</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-300"><strong class="text-white">Short answer:</strong> a tattoo portfolio gets found on Google when each style has its own indexable section, every image carries descriptive alt text, and the page loads fast on mobile. The prettiest portfolios rarely rank — the most <em>structured</em> ones do.</p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-gray-400">We build and host portfolio pages for 500+ tattoo studios, so we can see which structures pull search traffic and which sit invisible. Six patterns separate the two:</p>
      <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-ink-800 bg-ink-900/30 p-5"><h3 class="text-white font-semibold">1. Name the page after the work, not the shop</h3><p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-400">A title like "Fine Line Tattoo Portfolio — Austin" matches how clients actually search (style + city). A page titled only with your shop name competes for one query; a style-named page competes for dozens. This mirrors <a href="https://developers.google.com/search/docs/appearance/google-images" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google's own image SEO guidance</a> on descriptive, keyword-relevant context.</p></div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-ink-800 bg-ink-900/30 p-5"><h3 class="text-white font-semibold">2. Group by style so each section can rank on its own</h3><p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-400">Blackwork, Japanese, fine-line — separate, labelled categories let each block rank for its own term and let clients self-select. Across our studios, style-grouped galleries consistently surface for more long-tail image searches than one undifferentiated grid.</p></div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-ink-800 bg-ink-900/30 p-5"><h3 class="text-white font-semibold">3. Give every image real alt text</h3><p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-400">"Fine line rose, forearm, 2026" tells Google what the image is; "IMG_4857.jpg" tells it nothing. Alt text is what puts tattoo photos into image search — one of the largest discovery channels for artists. InkFlow generates alt text from your captions automatically, so no image ships blank.</p></div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-ink-800 bg-ink-900/30 p-5"><h3 class="text-white font-semibold">4. Show healed work, clearly labelled</h3><p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-400">Healed photos are the single strongest trust signal a tattoo portfolio can carry — they prove the work ages well, not just that it looks sharp on day one. Caption each with how long it has healed ("healed, 14 months") and keep a dedicated healed section. It converts browsers who already trust your style but want proof of longevity.</p></div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-ink-800 bg-ink-900/30 p-5"><h3 class="text-white font-semibold">5. Put a booking CTA on every view</h3><p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-400">A visitor who loves one photo should be one tap from booking that artist — not hunting for a contact button. A gallery that ranks but can't convert is a missed booking. InkFlow keeps the booking action visible as clients scroll.</p></div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-ink-800 bg-ink-900/30 p-5"><h3 class="text-white font-semibold">6. Keep it fast and mobile-first</h3><p class="mt-1 text-sm text-gray-400">Most clients browse on a phone, and Google indexes the mobile version of your page first. Heavy, uncompressed galleries fail <a href="https://web.dev/articles/vitals" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Core Web Vitals</a> and slide down the results. InkFlow compresses images and serves a mobile-built grid by default, so speed isn't something you have to manage.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

